Rationale: Most transplantation programs submit trans-plantation candidates to a rigorous cardiovascular evaluation, although the evidence basis for this approach is lacking. 
The 2014 updated Guideline on Pre-Transplant Cardiac Evaluation in Kidney and Liver Transplantation of the Canadian Society of Transplantation recommends pretransplant cardiac evaluation that includes the following:
(i) history and physical examination;
(ii) electrocardiogram (ECG);
(iii) transthoracic echocardiography with stress testing in patients aged >50 years old, or those <50 who have any of these risk factors-diabetes mellitus, hypertension, cigarette smoking, dyslipidemia (total cholesterol to high-density lipoprotein ratio ≥4), positive family history for premature coronary artery disease (men <55 years old and women <65 years old);
(iv) coronary angiography is recommended if the patient has clinical evidence of cardiac disease, abnormal ECG or stress test;
(v) pre-transplant myocardial perfusion scan, if available.
